1 admitted to the University of Texas after the United States Supreme Court's
2 decision in Brown v. Board of Education in 1954, but he still was not allowed
3 to attend because of his race; and
4
5 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr. was also accepted to attend Howard
6 University in Washington, D.C.; and
7
8 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr. attended the University of Arkansas at
9 Pine Bluff (then known as Arkansas Agricultural, Mechanical, and Normal
10 College) for his undergraduate degree and New York University for his
11 master's degree, then obtained his Juris Doctorate at Yale University; and
12
13 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr.'s first place of employment as an attorney
14 was with the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's
15 Legal Defense Fund in New York City, where he remained associated as a
16 cooperating attorney and later as a member of the Board of Directors of the
17 National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's Legal Defense
18 Fund; and
19
20 WHEREAS, in 1965, John W. Walker, Sr. began his law practice in Little
21 Rock with an emphasis on civil rights, and in 1968 opened one (1) of the
22 first three (3) racially integrated law firms in the South; and
23
24 WHEREAS, between 1965 and the time of his death, John W. Walker, Sr.
25 was personally involved in most of the reported cases involving racial
26 discrimination in the State of Arkansas, many of which created new law and
27 opened doors to all races in schools and places of work throughout the State
28 of Arkansas and surrounding states; and
29
30 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr. was intimately involved with the legal
31 battle to desegregate the Little Rock School District begun by the late Wiley
32 A. Branton of Pine Bluff and future Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall,
33 and Walker filed scores of successful lawsuits in federal courts to force
34 Arkansas school districts to integrate or provide coequal learning
35 environments; and
