1 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr.'s early cases often involved classes of
2 people discriminated against by large corporations due to their race; and
3
4 WHEREAS, by 1970, John W. Walker, Sr. had become famous statewide for
5 his nearly two (2) decades of prominent and tireless civil rights activism,
6 and was appointed to the Board of Education by then-Governor Winthrop P.
7 Rockefeller but was not confirmed to serve on the Board of Education; and
8
9 WHEREAS, one of John W. Walker, Sr.'s latter cases was the only
10 nationwide racial discrimination case ever successfully brought against
11 Walmart, Inc., and involved Black truck drivers; and
12
13 WHEREAS, John W. Walker, Sr. received numerous awards from bar
14 organizations including the American Civil Liberties Union, the National
15 Association for the Advancement of Colored People's Legal Defense Fund, and
16 the 2004 Southern Trial Lawyers Association's War Horse Award, and he was
17 inducted into the Arkansas Black Hall of Fame in 1999; and
18
19 WHEREAS, upon his death, the body of John W. Walker, Sr. lay in state
20 in the rotunda of the State Capitol Building and his picture remains on the
21 wall of the House of Representatives' Quiet Room,
22
23 NOW THEREFORE,
24 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE NINETY-FIFTH GENERAL
25 ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF ARKANSAS:
26
27 THAT the House of Representatives remember legendary civil rights
28 attorney and longtime State Representative John W. Walker, Sr. for his
29 lifelong fight against discrimination and his service to the State of
30 Arkansas.
31
32 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED THAT upon adoption, a copy of this resolution be
33 presented to the family of John W. Walker, Sr. by the Chief Clerk of the
34 House of Representatives.
